msDesc.head: Henricus de Frimaria, Quaestiones in quartum librum Sententiarum. Summa rudium

p.note: is the former pastedown which has been detached from the cover. carries offprint from the pastedown. is also loose and it is possible to lift it and look the text on the verso as well as the board underneath.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. Item ibi sunt

collation.p: VisColl collation. Parchment guards made from strips of an old manuscript.
collation.signatures: Two sets of quire signatures in Arabic numerals; the first visible at the first leaves of quires 5-9, the second on quire 12-13.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Originally, leather over bevelled wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Originally, corner and centre bosses. Catchplate and strap attachment plate of brass. , two damaged labels, the first one illegible; the second has what looks like 273 written in red ink.
binding.condition: Leather almost completely removed, only minute pieces remain. Holes on and after bosses. Straps missing. , the lables seem to have been reattached directly on the bookblock after the leather was removed. Board attachement visible on . Both covers carry signs of bookworms, is especially affected.

origin.p: Germany Bavaria , 1406 and 1427. The colophon on states that the text was finished in and the colophon for the second part on gives the year . In addition, at the bottom of is written. The second colophon also gives the name of the author, Master Joahnnes from Neuburg (probably Neuburg an der Donau).

provenance.p: According to the addition on the manuscript was given to the Carthusian monastery in Buxheim in 1435 by Master Johannes (the same year he died). The manuscript probably remained at the monastery library until the monastery was dissolved in . However, on and there are some short additions by a medieval hand in French, which indicates that the manuscript has either travelled or that a French speaker has travelled to the manuscript.

acquisition.p: Purchased by the National Library at the Stockholm City Book Auction (Stockholms stads bokauktionskammare) in .

supportDesc.condition: Minor staining throughout. Binding thread visible in gutter.

p.note: Top left corner, in ink by a medieval hand (perhaps the scribe): ? Summa Rudium et scriptis/scripture super? 4 sentenciarum; below, by an early modern hand: Cartusiae in Buxheim; inside the initial Q, by a medieval hand: gloriouse mere dieu; bottom of page: two National Library stamps (one smudged), in blue ink: 1956/5 (accession number), in black ink by an early modern hand: N 101.

Marginal adiditions by the scribe or a contemporary hands. The additions consist mainly of short corrections, the abbreviation for dubitatur (also found in the text) seems to be used as a keyword, and a type of rubric written in the bottom margin and keyed to the text with a signe-de-renovoi, e.g. on .
Top of page in brown ink by a medieval hand (the scribe?): In nomine domini; bottom of page: 1405.
Short additions in the margin by at least one medieval hand, most often keywords, e.g. , but in places some type of commentary has been written in a faint brown ink, e.g. on .
After the main text a medieval hand has written two lines in French.

msItem.finalRubric: Et sic terminatur summa Rudium autentica ad honorem gloriose virginis marie Et beati dominici patris nostri ordinis fratrum predicatorum et ad perfectum simplicium sacerdotum prestante domino nostro ihesu christo qui vnus est deus cum patre et sancto spiritu per omnia benedictus amen
msItem.note: The Summa rudium was printed by Johann Otmar in 1487.
